<font color="#FF0000">TO; JOSEPH, TOM &amp; TERRY</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul  1 11:26:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Joseph and Tom; <br>
Joseph, I agree with you on a number of points about Tet, and appreciate your studies in regards to Viet Nam War. There was a tremendous difference in the war I fought in Viet Nam as a Marine during 1967-1968 and what others fought afterwards. In your studies that is an important aspect to keep in mind. Those that came after us did not fight the same type of war. One of the reasons &quot;Charlie&quot; was never found by many units was that they went out in company size operations or even platoons size patrols. We engaged the enemy often because we usually went out as a squad,  9-12 men and a two men machine gun team. <br><br>
Tom answered part of your question. The Vietnamese villagers knew not to run. If they ran from the NVA or us, they were considered enemy. That is why many Vietnam documentary films show Marines walking around paddy fields while the farmer went about his business. They were often warned by their own forces not to run. We knew this and they knew this. <br>
Marines are trained for fire discipline. We were not robots there was no shortage of leadership abilities in the rank and file of a Marine rifle squad. Most of us during the time I served in Viet Nam were volunteers. The enemy knew where we stood watch at night so we did not give away our position. We knew that only ones coming near our perimeter wires at night would be Sappers, a well-trained communist soldier that was an expert in mine and demolitions and who caused us many causalities. If you saw them in the wire, you had better open up because you can rest assured that an attack was in progress. We also knew when they would only probe and often held our fire knowing that they would return. About an hour after I had gotten off watch a Sapper (frogmen) swam up the Song Thu Bond river and blew up Liberty Bridge whom the Seabees had just finished building a couple of days before. The Seabees weren't too happy about that especially when we laughed our heads off over how easily the bridge was torn apart. <br>
You are right about our enemy the NVA soldier was a worthy foe and we respected them as such. I have read Lannings book and agree. But the NVA had no allegiance to the South Vietnamese villager who saw them only as providers of their needs or the cause of their misery. <br>
To Tom (wingmen);<br>
I don't know why so many Vietnam vets demonstrated as you mention. I would venture to believe those that did, did not fight the war I fought and that many of them were not Vets at all. There are many things I still don't understand. Of the 47, Marines in my platoon only two suffer from any ill effects, PDS as it's called. They however were captured by the enemy and had to play dead at the foot of their trench line while I fired over their heads and the enemy returned fire over a six-hour period. When we finally were able to recover them they had been stripped of their weapons and clothing. They played dead all that time and I can understand why they have problems even today. The rest of the platoon went on to live very productive lives, however have remained silent all this time because they were trained to do as their country bid them and did so with honor against a strong communist force.  We fought a war as Americans proud to do so. Many died at my side and I would not dishonor their sacrifice by demonstrating because we had been lied to by those in higher responsibility. Terry Crenshaw makes a good point on this. <br>
As to the NVA soldier I let slip away. You missed the point. I heard his stomach growl, I saw the miscible condition he was in, and the pains and sorrows he had endured were clearly visible in his eyes. I was looking at a mirror. Here we were America's best fighting men in the jungles of Viet Nam and we had not been re-supplied, we had not eaten for days his clothing like mine had been tattered and torn. He probably saw me as I saw him. Many times in the jungles we came across individuals that we didn't know if we were suppose to shoot them or say good morning.  <br><br>

